Why AWS SQS (Simple Queue Service) was introduced?
--------------------------------------------------
AWS SQS was introduced to solve the problem of communication between different parts of a system — safely and reliably — without losing messages.


Imagine you have:
App A → sends data (order placed)
App B → processes data (generate invoice)
If App B is busy or down, App A can’t wait forever.
So SQS acts as a middleman (a queue) to hold the messages safely until B is ready.


User places order → App A sends directly to App B → App B is down ❌ → Order lost
User places order → App A sends message to SQS → App B reads message later ✅


Problem	                                                 SQS Solution
Direct system-to-system calls can fail if one is down	 SQS stores message until receiver is ready
Systems tightly coupled	                                 SQS decouples them
Message loss on errors	                                 SQS guarantees delivery (at least once)
Sudden traffic spikes crash backend	                     SQS buffers and smooths the load



SQS was introduced to ensure reliable, decoupled, 
and scalable communication between microservices — without losing messages, even when parts of the system fail.


What does "Decoupling" mean in AWS SQS?

Decoupling means separating two systems so they can work independently — without depending on each other’s speed, timing, or availability.

In other words:

The sender doesn’t need to wait for the receiver.

🔧 Without Decoupling (Tightly Coupled System)

Let’s say you have:

Order Service → sends order data

Email Service → sends confirmation email

If the Email Service is slow or down, the Order Service must wait or fails ❌



